==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sleave
<hw>Sleave</hw> <pr>(sl⟦emac⟧v)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Dan.
<ets>sl⟦oum⟧if</ets>, a knot loop, Sw. <ets>slejf</ets>, G.
<ets>schleife</ets> a knot, sliding knot, and E. <ets>slip</ets>,
v.i.]</ety> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The knotted or entangled part of silk or
thread.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Silk not yet twisted; floss; -- called
also <altname>sleave silk</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sleep that knits up the ravell'd <qex>sleave</qex> of care.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sleave</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sleave
<hw>Sleave</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sleaved</conjf> <pr>(sl⟦emac⟧vd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sleaving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To separate, as threads; to
divide, as a collection of threads; to sley; -- a weaver's
term.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sleaved</ent>⟦br⟧
